@node Declaring built-in or externally managed packages
@section Declaring built-in or externally managed packages

@findex use-feature
When your Emacs configuration uses an external package manager (such as @samp{elpaca}) that handles installation separately, every @samp{use-package} declaration for an already-installed package needs @samp{:ensure nil} to prevent @samp{use-package} from trying to install it again. The macro @code{use-feature} wraps @code{use-package} and automatically injects @samp{:ensure nil}, so you can write:

@lisp
(use-feature my-package
  :init
  (setq my-package-variable t)
  :config
  (my-package-mode 1))
@end lisp

This is equivalent to:

@lisp
(use-package my-package
  :ensure nil
  :init
  (setq my-package-variable t)
  :config
  (my-package-mode 1))
@end lisp

The macro accepts the same NAME and ARGS as @code{use-package}. It is also useful for configuring built-in Emacs features that do not need installation at all.

@node Creating interactive lambdas
@section Creating interactive lambdas

@findex lambda!
The macro @code{lambda!} provides a concise way to create anonymous interactive functions. It wraps the provided BODY forms in @code{(lambda () (interactive) ...)}, saving you from writing the boilerplate each time. For example:

@lisp
(lambda! (message "Hello!"))
@end lisp

expands to:

@lisp
(lambda () (interactive) (message "Hello!"))
@end lisp

This is particularly convenient in key-binding definitions and hook setups where a full @code{defun} would be excessive.

